{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"18131408-f8cb-4d4d-8b97-1526d1ecf29e","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\nThe **MCP Inspector** is a web-based tool for interactively testing MCP servers. Here's how to connect your stdio-based C# server:\n\n### 1. Launch the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourServer`\n\n### 3. Connect & Test\n\nClick **Connect**. Once connected you can:\n\n- **List Tools** — see all tools your server exposes\n- **Call Tools** — invoke them with test inputs and inspect responses\n- **List Resources/Prompts** — if your server exposes those\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Logging:** Your server must write MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** only. Use **stderr** for any diagnostic logging (`Console.Error.WriteLine()`), as stdout is the transport channel.\n- **Environment variables:** The Inspector UI lets you set env vars your server might need.\n- **Hot reload:** If you use `dotnet run`, you can stop/reconnect after code changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7dbf35d1-4cdd-4ac5-9086-5d5bbc51ffd6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"AC11:14E17:B87205:E43598:6A012D4B"},"id":"62070e8f-df5d-45bf-8f8c-4ff6ad00e028","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:59.196Z","parentId":"fd61dcf2-276c-4b17-84be-64cc290c7a29"}
